ce to antidiuretic hormone action","Deficiency of antidiuretic hormone production","Rare association with lithium therapy","Response to exogenous antidiuretic hormone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EADH promotes water reabsorption. Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus (DI) is characterized by resistance to antidiuretic hormone (ADH) at the kidney level, causing excessive urination and thirst. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChronic kidney disease\u003C/strong\u003E is not the primary cause of nephrogenic DI. The condition occurs due to \u003Cstrong\u003Eresistance to ADH action\u003C/strong\u003E at the receptor level in the collecting ducts, not due to \u003Cstrong\u003Edeficiency of ADH production\u003C/strong\u003E (which characterizes central DI).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELithium therapy is actually a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecommon association\u003C/strong\u003E with nephrogenic diabetes insipidus, not a rare one. Because the condition involves receptor dysfunction, there is no \u003Cstrong\u003Eresponse to exogenous antidiuretic hormone\u003C/strong\u003E administration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus is characterized by resistance to antidiuretic hormone at the kidney level, leading to excessive urination and thirst","Lithium therapy is a common cause of nephrogenic diabetes insipidus","Nephrogenic diabetes insipidus does not respond to exogenous antidiuretic hormone due to receptor dysfunction"],"references":["Mutter CM, Smith T, Menze O, Zakharia M, Nguyen H. Diabetes Insipidus: Pathogenesis, Diagnosis, and Clinical Management. Cureus. 2021 Feb 23;13(2):e13523. doi: 10.7759/cureus.13523. PMID: 33786230; PMCID: PMC7996474.","Priya G, Kalra S, Dasgupta A, Grewal E. Diabetes Insipidus: A Pragmatic Approach to Management. Cureus. 2021 Jan 5;13(1):e12498. doi: 10.7759/cureus.12498. PMID: 33425560; PMCID: PMC7785480.","Wass, J. A., \u0026 Stewart, P. M. (Eds.). (2011). Oxford textbook of endocrinology and diabetes. Oxford University Press, USA."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56092"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15623"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56092","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56092"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-16T12:35:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-16T12:35:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8314"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70627"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4929","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4929"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6d","name":"Endocrine","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:27+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"